      {
        "id": "3ce925e4-1753-43df-bc6b-1dbbf6646f77",
        "title": "Hiragana / Katakana",
        "type": "rich",
        "order_index": 1,
        "content": {
          "type": "doc",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "attrs": {
                "textAlign": null
              },
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "For this course, hiragana and katakana will remain the same as Japanese. There will be some changes:"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "attrs": {
                "textAlign": null
              },
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "| a| i| u| e| o ---|---|---|---|---|--- y| や （ヤ）| いぃ（イィ）| ゆ（ユ）| いぇ（イェ）| よ（ヨ） w| わ（ワ）| うぃ（ウィ）| うぅ（ウゥ）| うぇ（ウェ）| を（ヲ）"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "attrs": {
                "textAlign": null
              },
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Note that in some textbooks, they will use をぅ instead of うぅ, but just stick to what is in the chart for the sake of this course."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "attrs": {
                "textAlign": null
              },
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Also note that っ represents a glottal stop."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
